<span class="pubdate size11 darkgray" title="2003-11-08 13:20:00Z">Nov 8, 2003</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">Well:



Issue 1): The fact that the WAP as placed inside a data center that has good Physical Access Authentication (PIN + ID Card) gives me the impression of an insider's job. (Is their machine room shared by anyone else?).



Issue 2): The insider element is also reflected by the fact that when you use an Ethernet Bridge (the LinkSys WAP), you will need to have a pretty good knowledge of the IP settings for internal and external subnets. The IP rotation script that the smart ar** has devised also points to this fact. (How does he/she know exactly all the IPs that are not used?)



Issue 3): The MAC address of the intruder's laptop remains the same. 



There could be things that I don't know, but I would:

-Check from arp logs (servers switches) for that IP in the hotel chains IT infrastructure).

-When your sniffer detects the presence of this MAC, try to portscan the subnet (or the range of IPs that are rotated). OS Authentication and other ports should give you a clue. 



This is interesting :-). I could be wrong but someone from the Hotel Chain has a lot to account for ???



</span>
		</div>
           
