			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">8 AM, 6PM?

Sounds like rush hour traffic to me.  And, since this is the case of the Drive-By spammer, perhaps the relevant clue we're looking for.  Someone could park on the opposite side of the highway and be masked by the constant traffic.

</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="678512"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100337/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100337/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="pubdate size11 darkgray" title="2003-11-10 16:06:00Z">Nov 10, 2003</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">You said "WAP configured as an ethernet bridge"...don't bridges respond to ARP requests on behalf of the devices on the other side?



Also, don't some WAPs have a dhcp server built into them?



Taking both of those points together, you still might have more then one machine in the air...still running CRON/AT for sending the traffic at different times.



Or...maybe the traffic isn't coming over the WAP. Maybe the WAP is just used to admin a hacked box on the network....need to see what switch port this MAC is coming from.



</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="678514"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100337/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100337/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="pubdate size11 darkgray" title="2003-11-11 11:41:00Z">Nov 11, 2003</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">I may be way off base, but the 8:00am and 6:00pm strike me as very significant.  It is as if someone with a laptop is parking outside the building and accessing the network via the wireless rig just before they go on shift and just after they get off their shift.  The proximity of the service road in the back would make this extremely easy.  WHar is happening with the neighboring business may be RF overflow by proximity, or may be an entirely differnt intrusion case.  Would this require separate billing?  Just a thought.  They could even be an employee of the hotel chain and have their car parked back there.  It would be very interesting to be sitting out there at 5:45 that afternoon to see who does what.  Likewise, the formal parking lot may be well within range.  The MAC address given is the only way to link the person in their car to the crime as it is using wireless.  Well, there are other ways, but that is probably the best.  A seccurity camera covering that side of the buuilding should get what you need to be a warrant for the guy's laptop and that will confirm the MAC address.</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
