<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100337/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="pubdate size11 darkgray" title="2003-11-12 10:55:00Z">Nov 12, 2003</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">In thinking about it a little more, it is probably a LOT easier for the spammer to sit around with a wireless network card then to hack into one of their systems....</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="678542"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100337/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100337/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="pubdate size11 darkgray" title="2003-11-12 12:49:00Z">Nov 12, 2003</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">Kaleb,

   I think that the person doing the spamming is an employee of the hotel chain who either works in the data center, or has access.  For example; a CS student, working as a night cleaner, would have the requisite knowledge.  That person could take a couple minutes, while finishing his / her coffee in the car in the morning and send off the morning load of spam from the car, parked either out back, or if range permitted, from the front parking lot.  Then again, if the range is sufficient, they could be sitting at the coffee shop nearby!  For the 1800 spam load, it could be when the worker gets off and goes out to their car.  If the spammer works for a cleaning service that cleans both businesses, that could explain the compromise of the company next door, with a second wireless router.  Physical access, at some point, is obvious.  The wireless router got into the data center.  Whether the intruder works there, broke in, or used social engineering skill and posed as a telephone repaiman is at this point unknown.  The two daily points of contact are both remote, as it involves wireless transmission.  At about 0800 and 1800 the individual is within range briefly and makes the connection.  Using RDF equipment on the carrier frequency of the wireless router, to triangulate his exact position might be necessary.  Especcially if he is just stopping briefly, and then driving on.  If he's sitting, parked in a lot, then he can be walked up on and observed.  Either way, the MAC address of his NIC in the laptop is the smoking gun and will be what ties him to the intrusions.</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>


</div>

    
    
